revision.text:
[[File:Kofunmatsuri.jpg|thumbnail|Saito Kofun Festival – Flame Ceremony]]
'''Saito Kofun Festival''' ({{ill|Saito Kofun Festival|ja|西都古墳まつり|12=draft|12=draft}}) is a {{ill|Festival in Japan|ja|祭り|12=draft|12=draft}} held primarily in {{ill|Saitobaru|ja|西都原|12=draft|12=draft}}, located in {{ill|Saito, Miyazaki|ja|西都市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Miyazaki Prefecture. The festival also takes place in other venues such as the city center of Saito, {{ill|Tsuma Shrine|ja|都萬神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, and the surrounding areas. The event is linked to the {{ill|Saitobaru Kofun Group|ja|西都原古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}}, which is situated several hundred meters west of the city center.

The festival’s origins date back approximately 600 years to records of the {{ill|Tenson Kōrin|ja|天孫降臨|12=draft|12=draft}} Festival and Imperial Mausoleum Festival at Miyake Shrine, located between the Saitobaru Plateau and the city. However, the festival took its current form in the late Shōwa era. It is held annually over two days on the first Saturday and Sunday of November.

The first day features events such as a {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽|12=draft|12=draft}} festival, a torch procession, and the Flame Ceremony. On the second day, ceremonial events and dedication rituals take place.

The festival includes a torch procession, where local citizens and city employees dressed in period clothing from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}} march through the area. A highlight is the Flame Ceremony, in which city employees reenact a myth from the {{ill|Himuka Mythology|ja|日向神話|12=draft|12=draft}}, specifically the story of {{ill|Ninigi-no-Mikoto|ja|ニニギノミコト|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|コノハナサクヤヒメ|12=draft|12=draft}}. The roles of Ninigi-no-Mikoto and Konohanasakuya-hime must be played by unmarried employees. The festival also features traditional performing arts from Saito, including the nationally designated Important Intangible Folk Cultural Property {{ill|Shimizu Usudaiko Dance|ja|下水流臼太鼓踊|12=draft|12=draft}} and other local {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽|12=draft|12=draft}} performances.

The festival is one of the few opportunities to access the grounds of the {{ill|Ozasahozuka Kofun|lt=Ozasahozuka|ja|男狭穂塚|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Mezasahozuka Kofun|ja|女狭穂塚|lt=Mezasahozuka Kofuns|12=draft|12=draft}}, which are usually off-limits as Imperial {{ill|Mausoleum Reference Site|ja|陵墓参考地|lt=Mausoleum Reference Sites|12=draft|12=draft}}



